{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_aetna_ver02/data/sn92060454/00393346759/1945091501/0156.xml":{"full_text":"I'V /riPIlT _ I \u201cINASMUCH as most good things are I\nI 11 n I '\\M BHBwl J^\u00a3 W 9 produced by labor, it follows that\n^H(4n A f /T F SMI _ such things ought to belong to those\nteS* MARKET! if fil> l|t4f1ff lYtY (I ttWfrCl Ssffi'S&S\n1 1\u201411 %r J IV' 1^ W11' J lV'>9 sx;\u2122idl^nu\u2122;\u2122\u2018^ns\neach laborer the whole product of his\nj C^rr I TIT I I r I labor as nearly as possible is a worthy\n'_ElSfillSlllS&l Official Weekly Labor Organ Voicing The Interests Of The American Federation of Labor fb^Lm uHLin^ gover,,menl\n\\/OT C XJ,-, 9 1 Entered as Second Class Matter May 5, 1941, at the Post Office\n1NU. LL lt New TjaveBi Conn., under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNEW HAVEN, CONN., SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 15, 1945\nA.F.L. NEWS SERVICE PRICE 5 CENTS\nTruman Stresses Human Reconversion\n[Federation Raps Governors U. C. Policy\nLeaders Attack\nHis OppositionTo\nGovernment Aid\njFeinmark, Collins Wonder\nIf Labor Commissioner\nEgan Was Consulted\nSharp criticism of Gover\nnor Raymond E. Baldwin for\nhis opposition to the Kilgore\nForand bill which provides\nfor Federal supplementation\nof existing state unemploy\nment compensation benefits\nwas expressed by the Con\nnecticut Federation of Labor\nin a joint statement issued l\u00bby\nTimothy M. Collins and Har\nold. V. Feinmark, President\nand Secretary-Treasurer re\nspectively of the state Ameri\ncan Federation of Labor or\nganization.\nj Human Needs\n\u201cBy his action in instructing\nActing Director James J. Graham\nof the State Employment Security\nDivision of the Department of\nLabor to file a statement with the\nSenate Finance Committee oppos\ning the proposal recommended by\nPresident Harry 5. Truman and\nstrongly favored by labor, \u201cthe\nAmerican Federation of Labor\nofficials said, \u201cGovernor Baldwin\nhas lined up with forces hostile\nto measures needed to deal ade\nquately with the human side of\nreconversion problems.\n\u201cConnecticut\u2019s present unem\nployment compensation law limits\npayments to 18 weeks annually,\nand two weeks additional will be\npaid only after January 1, 1946.\nIt is still not clear whether workers\nwho have lost their jobs prior to\nthis date will be entitled to 20\n/'weeks payment or not. Judging by\nthe present attitude of the State\nEmployment Security Division it\nseems to be more concerned with\nfinding technicalities for husband\ning the Fund built up in the war\nyears than in using it for the pur\npose for which it was created,\nnamely, to tide over workers who\nare jobless through no fault of\ntheir own during this emergency\nRoeriod.\u201d\nTelegram To Egan\nThey made public a telegram sent\nto Commissioner of Labor John J.\nEgan, on August 24th as follows:\n\u201cConnecticut Federation of Labor\nheartily supports Senate Bill 1274\nand House Bill 3891 providing for\nFederal supplementation of exist\ning state unemployment compen\nsation benefits on the grounds that\nCongress has adopted legislation\nto aid business, farmers and vet\nerans during the emergency re\nconversion period but neglected to\nprovide for adequate unemploy\nment compensation for discharged\nwar workers, as pointed out by\nPresident Truman. Respectfully\nsuggest your department be repre\nsented at Congressional hearings\nnext week to register support of\nthis legislation. This would be very\nhelpful and would be greatly ap\npreciated by Connecticut Federa\ntion of Labor. Kindly advise.\nSigned: Timothy M. Collins and\nHarold V. Feinmark.\u201d\nA reply received by Secretary\nTreasurer Feinmark under date of\nAugust 27th from Deputy Commis\nsioner William E. Ennis merely said\nthe Department would be represented\nat the hearing by Mr. Graham.\nWas Egan Consulted?\n\u201cIt would be interesting to know,\u201d\nthey added, \u201cwhether Governor Bald\nwin sought the views of Commis\nsioner Egan on the Kilgore-Forand\nbill before instructing Mr. Graham\nto appear against it.\u201d\nGERMAN CO-OP REOPENED\nThe former German cooperative\nwholesale society, which in pre-Hitler\ndays served some 900 cooperative\n1 societies with three million members\nis open for business again in Hamburg\nwith the consent of the British mili\ntary government. The organization\nwas taken over by the Nazi labor\nfront in 1933, its leading officers were\n1 dismissed or demoted and when the\nmajority of its affiliated societies were\nsmashed, the wholesale was reorgan\nized as a company.\nmoo aaodSiUTyi\n0 IHflOO AHVUQn\nHSJ.C: !T\u2018ia S\u00ab\nSends Protest\nJAMES O\u2019KANE, secretary\ntreasurer of the Conn. Building\nand Construction Trades Coun\ncil, B. A. of Iron Workers, No.\n424, who has sent a sharp pro\ntest to Washington on the con\ntinuation of the authority of the\nWage Adjustment Board over\nbuilding trades wage scales.\n(Story on this page.)\nAs We See It\nby\nTHE STAFF\nTHE A. F. of L. this week cited\nofficial figures to show that, be\ncause of sensational advances in\nproductivity of American workers\nduring the war, industry can\nreadily pay higher wages, without\nhiking prices.\nStatistics of the War Production\nBoard and Department of Labor\ndisclose a rise of 47 per cent in\nproduction per man-hour in muni\ntions industries and of 25 per cent\nin all manufacturing during the\nwar, the Federation pointed out,\nin driving home its argument.\nPresident William Green of the\nA. F. of L. contended that not only\nwill much of this higher efficiency\ncarry over into peacetime, but as\n---i\nWartime Strike Loss\nUnder Peace Years\nContrary to propaganda in\nthe newspapers, \u201cthe percentage\nof lost time from all strikes dur\ning the war was far below the\nlosses of peacetime years,\u201d\nChairman George W. Taylor of\nthe National War Labor Board\ndeclared this week.\n\u201cIn addition, strikes were\nhalted far more quickly than\never before in history,\u201d he said.\n\u201cThe wartime voluntary pro\ngram for peaceable settlements\nhas indeed served America\nwell.\u201d _\nindustry reconverts, puts in new\nmachinery and applies new tech\nniques developed during the war,\nproductivity will zoom further.\n\u201cThese measures will so increase\nproductivity thaT experts believe\nthe first three post-war years will\nbring a 30 per cent gain in pro\nduction per man-hour in American\nfactories,\u201d Green said.\nSuch steady advance of produc\ntivity makes it imperative, he in\nsisted, that wages be increased\n\u201cevery year\u201d if workers are to be\nable to buy back a proper share\nof what they produce and if an\neconomic nosedive is to be averted.\n\nTHE financial affluence with\nwhich nearly all industrial corpor\n(Continued from Page Four)\nEighteen Doctors\nNeed Job Badly!\nPITTSBURGH (LPA)\u2014Eighteen\n\u201cdoctors\u201d applied for the job when\nDr. Betty Hayes\u2014as a protest against\nthe intolerably filthy conditions im\nposed on the workers by the Shawmut\nMining Co.\u2014walked out. The com\npany is willing to pay a \u201cdoctor\u201d but\nwill do nothing about the disease\nbreeding outdoor privies which con\ntaminate the town\u2019s drinking water.\nHowever, the members of the\nUnited Mine Workers refused to ac\ncept the company's nominees for the\nposition, and use the services of Dr.\nHayes on a private fee basis.\nNew Haven Voices\nIts Protest Over\nCongress\u2019 Inaction\nMass Meeting Calls For Special Session Of Conn. Legis\nlature\u2014Says Congress Must Take Responsibility For\nEnacting Laws To Prevent Another Mass Depression\nThe people of New Haven believe that upon Congress\n\u201crests the responsibility for enacting into law, measures\nwhich will help prevent another mass depression.\u201d\nThis was the unanimous vote of the protest mass meeting held\nWednesday night at the Labor Temple under the auspices of the\nGreater New Haven Committee for Full Employment and Pros\nperity, which is composed of the Central.Labor Council, the Rail\nroad Brotherhoods, C.I.O. Industrial Union Council, and a num\nber of civic and fraternal organizations.\nHighly Successful\nFeinmark Urges\nFull Attendance\nAtCapitolSept.18\nLabor Wants Special Legis\nlative Session To Help\nOn Reconversion\nLeaders of A.F.L. organizations\nin Connecticut have been urgently\nrequested by Harold V. Feinmark,\nsecretary-treasurer of the Connecti\ncut Federation of Labor, to attend\nthe public hearing scheduled by\nthe Connecticut Legislative Coun\ncil on Sept. 18, and press for a\nspecial session of the General As\nsembly to enact legislation which\nwill help carry the state over the\nreconversion period.\nFollowing is the telegram sent out\nby Feinmark:\n\u201cConnecticut Legislative Council\nholding public hearing at State Capi\ntol, Tuesday, Sept. 18 at 10:30 A.M.\non issue of recommending to Gover\nnor Baldwin special session of Legis\nlature.\n\u201cStrongly urge you attend and\nspeak for special session. Labor de\nmanded it so that Legislature can\nact on increased unemployment\nbenefits; draft a real public works\nprogram to help in conversion\nperiod; and to legislate for 65\ncents minimum wage for entire\nstate.\n\u201cPlease notify as many as pos\nsible in your area to attend. This\nis important meeting.\u201d\nElm City Bids\nFor Federation\u2019s\nState Convention\nWill Support Reconversion\nMeeting To Be Called\nBy Rep. Geelan\nThe New Haven Central Labor\nCouncil, at its meeting Thursday,\nvoted to invite the Connecticut\nFederation of Labor to hold its\nforthcoming convention in the Elm\nCity. Acting upon Council instruc*\ntions, Secretary John Redmond\nsent the following letter to Harold\nV. Feinmark, secretary-treasurer of\nthe State Federation:\n\u201cDear Sir and Brother:\n\u201cThe Central Labor Council of New\nHaven, Conn., by unanimous vote, at\nIts meeting Thursday, September 6,\nwent on record extending an invita\ntion to the Annual Convention of the\nState Federation to meet in the City\nof New Haven for its next annual\ngathering.\n\u201cWe were informed by Delegate\nSherman that the State body would\nprobably hold a meeting within a few\nmonths. We feel that New Haven\nwould be an ideal city for the con\nvention. We have every facility to\nhandle the meetings, and also to look\nafter the welfare of the delegates.\n\u201cWe hope that the officers respon\nsible for picking the City for the next\nconvention will give every considera\ntion to our city.\u201d\nSupport Geelan Meeting\nThe Council voted full support to\na meeting to discuss the problems of\nreconversion to be called .soon by\nRep. James P. Geelan. President Vin\ncent J. McGovern appointed the fol\nlowing committee to represent the\n(Continued on Page Three)\nThe meeting was a highly suc\ncessful, and was presided over by\nClifford W. Kealey, general chair\nman of the Brotherhood of Loco\nmotive Engineers. The speakers in\ncluded Mayor John W. Murphy,\nHarold V. Feinmark, secretary\ntreasurer of the Connecticut Fed\neration of Labor; Rep. James P.\nGeelan; Prof. Richard Bennett of\nYale University; Timothy Flynn,\ninternational representative of the\nC.I.O.; and William F. Donoghue,\nstate chairman of the Brotherhood\nof Railroad Trainmen.\nIn addition to the speeches, the high\nspot of the meeting was the action\non the resolutions, presented by the\nresolutions committee. One resolution\nsummed up the legislation which or\nganized labor favors on a national\nscale, and one urged Gov. Raymond\nE. Baldwin to call a special session\nof the Legislature. The text of this\nresolution follows:\no-roint rrogram\n\u201cResolved, that we, citizens of\nGreater New Haven, assembled at\nthe New Haven Labor Temple under\nthe auspices of the Greater New\nHaven Committee for Full Employ\nment and Prosperity, do herewith re\nquest Governor Raymond E. Baldwin\nto call a special session of the Con\nnecticut General Assembly so that our\nstate, together with Congress and the\nother states in the Union, may do its\nshare in solving some of the difficult\nproblems which lie ahead of us in\nthe reconversion period. This special\nsession, we are convinced, should:\n\u201cEnact legislation providing for\na full program of public works by\nthe State of Connecticut;\n\u201cSet a minimum wage of 65\ncents per hour for private indus\ntry so that our working people and\ntheir families may maintain the\nAmerican standard of living and\nhave purchasing power adequate to\nbuy the products they manufac\nture;\n\u201cImprove our unemployment\ncompensation law, so that those\nwho are unable to obtain jobs at\ndecent wage rates during the re\nconversion period, shall not suffer.\n(Continued on Page Three)\nI.L.C. In Norwalk\nHelps 100 With\nRenewal Raises\nHealth Benefits And Higher\nMinimums Won At\nLuxor Sportswear\nContract renewals, providing im\nproved terms for more than 100\nworkers in three South Norwalk\nshops, are reported by Organizer Lou\nOrons, of the International Ladies\nGarment Workers Union. All these\nworkers are members of Local 167.\nThe renewal of the pact with the\nLuxor Sportswear Co. brings health\nbenefits and higher minimums to\nthe 30 workers employed by this\nfirm. In addition, piece-rates are\nreadjusted upward and floor-work\ners and special machine operators\nget a $2 weekly increase.\nAt the Perfect Robe Co. the firm\u2019s\n25 workers have likewise won\nhealth benefits and higher mini\nmums in renewal of the union\u2019s\nagreement.\nNegotiations with the M S Robe\nCo., whose pact will not expire for\nsome time to come, have resulted in\nthe installation of an incentive plan\nfor the 50 workers involved which\nimmediately yielded a 12 per cent\nincrease in earnings and is expected to\nresult in an even greater increase in\nthe near future.\n*---4\nEmergency Case, No. 1\n0\nLET'S GET HIM\nIN FIRST',\n|S\u00a73\nState\u2019s Building\nTrades Ask End\nOf Wage Board\nThe business agents of all building trades unions in the\nstate affiliated with the Connecticut State Building and Con\nstruction Trades Council are asked to attend the next meet\ning of the executive board of the State Council, which will be\nheld at the New Haven Labor Temple on Wednesday, Oct. 3\nat 11 A.M.\nState-Wide Basis\nThis action was taken by the\nexecutive board at its regular\nmonthly meeting, when it was\nvoted that beginning with the\nOctober session, quarterly meetings\nof the board would consist of a\nstate-wide meeting of all business\nagents whose locals are members\nof the State Council.\n\u201cIt will be a good thing for the I\nbusiness agents of the building trades\nof Connecticut to get together every\nthree months and discuss their joint\nproblems,\u201d President Michael J.\nBarry of the State Council said, j\n\u201cThere are a number of important\nmatters which need our attention, and\nthe list is growing. Wage scales, the\nlength of the work week, the exten-1\nsion of our organizing campaign are\nissues which need the broadest con-,\nsideration we can give them. This is\na step in the right direction.\u201d The'\nexecutive board, under the plan\nadopted Wednesday, will continue to\nhold its regular meetings the first\nWednesday in each month between\nthe quarterly meetings.\nOne of the high spots of the\nmeeting was the unanimous feeling\nagainst General Order No. 41,\nwhich provides that wage rates for\nmembers of building and construc\ntion unions must still be approved\nby the Wage Adjustment Board,\nwhose authority has been extended\nuntil Nov. 18, 1945.\nStraight To Washington\nIn accordance with a vote of the\nboard that the State Council protest\nthis action, Secretary-Treasurer James\nO\u2019Kane immediately sent the follow\ning letter to Herbert Rivers, secretary\nof the A.F.L.\u2019s building and con\nstruction trades department in Wash\nington\n\u201cDear Sir and Brother:\n\u201cWe of the Connecticut State\nBuilding Construction Trades\nCouncil wish to be placed on\nrecord as being absolutely and com\npletely at a loss to understand the\nreasons for General Order No. 41\n(Continued on Page Three)\nWorkers\u2019 Savings Low\nWASHINGTON\u2014(LPA)\u2014\u201cSav\nings are concentrated in the hands of\na small minority, perhaps 10 to 25%\nof all individuals,\u201d says an editorial\nin the Washington Post. Liquid\nfinancial assets, although they have\nalmost tripled in the war years, can\nnot support a prolonged period of\nidleness in labor\u2019s rank and file, the\npaper continues, and \u201cthe concen\ntrated distribution of savings empha\nsizes the need for insurance to tide\nthe great majority of demobilized\nwar workers over the waiting period\nbetween jobs.\u201d\nNo Delicate Odor\nTokyo Rose, the girl who\nbroadcast Japanese propaganda\nto the Allies, has a new audi\nence. She sold her story to Wil\nliam Randolph Hearst for $2,000,\nAlfred G. Larke of Federated\nPress reports from Yokahama.\nTokyo Rose is really Iva Toguri,\nan American-born girl of Japa\nnese descent. (Federated Pic\ntures.)\n\u2018Nation's Goal Is\nFull Employment\u2019\nPresident Solidly Behind Labor\u2019s Program\u2014Lists Full\nProduction, High Standard Of Living As Country\u2019s\nObjective\u2014Action By Congress Imperative\nWASHINGTON (LPA) The Congress of the United\nMates has the responsibility to act on the problems that have\ncrowded down upon us with the surrender of the Japanese,\u201d\nPresident Truman said in his message sent to the House and\nsenate last week.\nA major share of Truman\u2019s message was devoted to the\nproblems of human reconversion. The nation\u2019s goals, in the\nchangeover to peacetime, were summarized by the chief ex\necutive as \u2018\u2022\u2018\u2022full production, full employment, and a high\nstandard of living.\u201d\nHere is President Truman\u2019s list on which Congress must\nact in coming months:\n1. Unemployment Compensation\nHe reiterated earlier proposals to provide emergency sup\nplements to state unemployment benefits up to $25 a week\nfor 26 weeks, and to extend coverage to Federal workers,\nmaritime workers and others. Truman vigorously assailed\nthose who charge the Kilgore Bill embodying these proposals\nwould undermine the present jobless benefit system, and\nlisted what the hill does not do.\u201d It is, he said, \u201cdesigned\nto meet the immediate pressing human problems of recon\nversion.\u201d\n2. Minimum Wage\nUrged immediate and substantial upward revision\u201d of\nthe present 40 cents minimum standard for wages in inter\nstate commerce set in the Fair Labor Standards Act. \u201cThe\nfoundations of a healthy national economy cannot be secure\nConnecticut Federation Hails Truman\nThe following telegram was sent Thursday, Sept. 6:\n\u201cPresident Harry S. Truman\u201d\n\u201cThe White House\u201d\n\u201cWashington, D. C.\u201d\n\u201cOrganized labor in Connecticut is proud that our President\nthrough his message to Congress today, has recognized the many\neconomic problems which face our returning veterans and bur\nwar workers.\n\u201cYour recommendations, if enacted into law, will help keep\nour country on an even keel, and will benefit all sections of our\npeople, especially the common man.\n\u201cWe pledge our full support to this splendid program, and\nwill inform our representatives in Congress that we expect them\nto equal your statesmanship by adopting this program without\nunnecessary delay.\n\u201cOur warmest congratulations and thanks.\u201d\n\u201cHAROLD V. FEINMARK\u201d,\n\u201cSecretary-Treasurer\u201d.\n\u201cConnecticut Federation of Labor\u201d.\nas long as any large section of our working people receive\nsubstandard wages. The existence of substandard wage levels\nsharply curtails the national purchasing power.\u201d Extension\nof the Act\u2019s provisions to agricultural processing workers,\nand elimination of a \u201ctwilight zone\u201d of workers who may or\nmay not be covered was urged by the President.\n3. Wartime Controls\nOur policy must guard against the contingencies both of\ninflation and of lower incomes and widespread unemploy\nment. It will be necessary for OPA to continue \u201cto resist un\nreasonable pressures for higher prices on some commodities\u201d\njust as it has been doing during the war. The Price Adminis\ntrator, Truman added, \u201chas both my backing and my confi\ndence.\u201d Wage rate increases that would imperil price ceilings\nwill likewise be resisted.\nThe \u2018\"short range policy\u201d followed by some businessmen,\nand \u201cdesigned to secure prices high enough to provide im\nmediate profits over and above their temporarily high costs\nof production due to their low volume\u201d was hit by Truman.\n\u201cThe promise of good profits for businessmen must not be\nbased on small initial volume. It must be based on the full\nall-out production which it is my belief that American indus\ntry will rapidly achieve.\u201d\n4. Full Employment\nRepeating to the members of Congress the economic bill\nof rights put forth by the late President Roosevelt, Truman\nasked for passage of the full employment bill as aiding in\ncarrying out these rights through full production and full\nemployment at decent wages. He asked \u201cearly action.\u201d\n5. FEPC\nThe President repeated his recommendation that the Fair\nEmployment Practice Committee be made permanent, to\ncarry on the work begun by the Federal Government during\nthe war years to remove \u201cinjustices based upon considera\ntions of race, religion and color.\u201d This, he said, \u201cis one of\nthe fundamentals of our political philosophy and should be\nan integral part of our economy.\u201d\n6. Wages and Labor Relations\nReported that he was calling the labor-management confer\nence \u201cfor the purpose of working out by agreement means to\nminimize labor disputes.\u201d Summarized his wage policy\norder. Reported that plans to strengthen the Dept, of Labor\nare going forward, and reiterated his belief that \u201ccollective\nbargaining and voluntary arbitration\u201d are \u201cthe best and most\ndemocratic method of maintaining sound industrial rela\ntions.\u201d\n(Continued on Page Two)","height":"26535","width":"20703"}}
